[13:58:41] {"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nAfter searching with V6B 1A1:\n- Count: 34 `button.primary-button` buttons\n- Index 0: \"SEARCH STORES\" \n- Index 1: \"Set Store\" (first result) ← this is what `firstSetStoreButton = nth(1)` targets\n- Index 2,3,4...: More \"Set Store\" buttons\n\nSo the selector IS correct! The `firstSetStoreButton = dialog#store-selector button.primary-button` nth(1) targets the first \"Set Store\" result button.\n\nOn the live site, there are 34 buttons. The results loaded. The issue on Firefox/Webkit is that after clicking \"SEARCH STORES\", the results are NOT showing up within 15s.\n\nThis is a NETWORK timing issue for Firefox. The search results take longer to appear on Firefox/Webkit because:\n1. Firefox/Webkit are slower at loading resources\n2. The store search API call takes time\n3. 15s might not be enough for the full flow on Firefox\n\nThe fix: Increase the timeout in `searchStores()` from 15s to 30s.\n\nAlso, on the `waitFor` call inside `searchStores`: the test waits for `firstSetStoreButton` (nth(1)) to be visible with 15s timeout. This needs to be increased to at least 25-30s for Firefox.\n\nLet me also look at if there's a need to wait for the search to complete before looking for results (maybe an intermediate state).\n\nSimple fix: In `ProductDetailPage.ts` `searchStores()`, increase `firstSetStoreButton` timeout from 15_000 to 30_000.\n\nAlso check if the issue could be that after clicking the search button, there's a loading spinner that we need to wait for to disappear before looking for results.\n"}}
